description.plain:
Swedish House Mafia is a supergroup consisting of the three successful Swedish DJs – Axwell, Sebastian Ingrosso and Steve Angello – founded in 2008. After five years and two mix albums, they initially disbanded in March 2013. The group then reunited five years later as a “surprise” guest closing out the 20th Ultra Music Festival following heavy rumors and various teasers started to show up in the Miami area.

Around seven months later, on October 22, 2018, the trio officially announced their reunion at a press conference in Stockholm. It was preceded by a countdown in the days leading up to the announcement. The Save the World Reunion Tour followed in 2019, but the trio did not release new music until putting out “It Gets Better” on July 15, 2021 – their first release since “Don’t You Worry Child” nearly nine years prior. Swedish House Mafia released their first studio album, Paradise Again, on April 15, 2022.

description.plain:
“Don’t You Worry Child” is the sixth and the final single released by Swedish House Mafia before their initial disbandment in 2013.

This song talks about innocence and its loss. The speaker’s childhood and teenage years were some of the best times of his life, and now, as an adult, he finds himself in a tough situation, only to be reminded of his father’s words of wisdom. The song also discusses destiny in that if things are meant to be, they will find a way.

songs.title: Save the World

description.plain:
“We wanted to make something that sums everything up after a two- or three-hour DJ set. It connects everybody to something pretty emotional and uplifting. We wanted our own end of the night track, and that was the idea behind ‘Save the World.’” – Swedish House Mafia

Steve Angello also mentioned in an interview with Artist Direct that they, as a group, were aiming to find a balance between a heavy instrumental and melodic feel to the song, but mix it with the house energy that they were so fond of.

The song was a great success and was well-received by critics, peaking at number 1 of Billboard’s Hot Dance Club Songs.
